# Mozart AI Compose — Decision Log
# Records key architectural and design decisions with rationale.
# Format: date | decision | rationale | alternatives considered

2026-03-01 | Bootstrap spec corpus before implementing Phase 1 code
  Rationale: TDF analysis revealed bootstrap paradox — can't build a specification
  engineering system while your own project has no specification corpus. Creating
  .mozart/spec/ by hand first provides both the dogfooding test case AND the
  development guide for Phases 1-9.
  Alternatives: (1) Implement Phase 1 code first, then create spec corpus — rejected
  because agents working on Phase 1 would have no spec to follow. (2) Generate spec
  corpus from existing docs — rejected because it would be a derivative, not a source
  of truth.

2026-03-01 | Restructure CLAUDE.md to put intent before mechanics
  Rationale: CLAUDE.md is the preamble for every Claude Code instance working on
  Mozart. The Four Disciplines primer says context engineering determines quality
  ceiling. Previous CLAUDE.md was mechanical reference (Discipline 1). New version
  leads with WHY (Discipline 3), references spec corpus (Discipline 4), then
  provides mechanics (Discipline 1).
  Alternatives: (1) Keep CLAUDE.md as-is and put intent in separate file — rejected
  because CLAUDE.md is the only file guaranteed to be read. (2) Inline all spec
  corpus content into CLAUDE.md — rejected because it would be 800+ lines and
  violate context engineering (include relevant tokens, exclude irrelevant ones).

2026-03-01 | Design 8-layer agent input structure for Mozart-orchestrated agents
  Rationale: Agents currently get preamble + prompt + patterns + validations. The
  Four Disciplines analysis revealed they lack organizational identity, decision
  authority, specification framing, institutional knowledge, and self-check
  protocols. The 8-layer design adds these without breaking existing functionality
  (all new layers are additive and opt-in via config).
  Alternatives: (1) Bake everything into the preamble — rejected because preamble
  is already specific (retry state, parallel mode) and this is different in kind.
  (2) Use prelude/cadenza system — partially applicable but these are per-score
  file injections, not system-level agent infrastructure.

2026-03-02 | Corrected conductor vs composer terminology across spec corpus
  Rationale: Post-interview review revealed the spec files still conflated
  "conductor" (the daemon process) with "composer" (the person using Mozart).
  The interview established that: conductor = daemon, composer = person (human
  or AI), musician = agent, instrument = backend. The original files said
  things like "any conductor — human or AI" and "conductor types: human,
  rlf_person, agent" which contradicted the metaphor. All five files corrected
  to use consistent terminology. Escalation model renamed from "conductor_chain"
  to "oversight_chain" (musician → conductor → composer).

2026-03-02 | Spec corpus verified and updated via mozart init interview
  Rationale: The spec corpus was created by AI from codebase analysis. The init
  interview surfaced the human's actual intent, which differed in significant ways.
  Key changes:
  - intent.yaml: Layered vision (spec engineering → collaborative intelligence →
    recursive dream). Conductor-agnostic design (not human-assumed). Conductor-chain
    escalation model. Planning is in-scope. Scope boundaries defined (Mozart IS
    orchestration + planning, IS NOT personhood/identity).
  - constraints.yaml: 3 new MUST-NOTs (MN-013: don't assume sole agent, MN-014:
    don't commit all files, MN-015: don't commit scores/plans without request).
    8 new preferences (P-011-P-018: production quality, simplicity, modularity,
    no dead code, adversarial testing, defensive coding everywhere, extensive
    logging, clean error taxonomy). Escalation reframed as conductor-chain.
  - quality.yaml: Test quality over test count. Adversarial testing emphasis.
    Review checklist rewritten to reflect human's actual priorities. Evolution
    quality refocused on "does it work in production."
  - conventions.yaml: 3 new musical terms (libretto=spec corpus, composer=planner,
    fermata=escalation pause). Design principles added (single source of truth,
    ECS ethos, defensive coding). Conductor term updated to not assume human.
  - architecture.yaml: Reframed from layers to musical performance model.
    Composer/conductor/musician/instrument roles clarified. Conductor is the
    daemon (adaptive execution system), not a person. Composers are the people.
    4 new invariants. Invariant 6 revised (learning store self-maintaining, not
    append-only).

2026-02-15 | Conductor-first architecture for all CLI operations
  Rationale: Issue #50. mozart run was executing jobs directly when no conductor
  was running, creating two execution paths. Unified to always route through
  conductor IPC. Only --dry-run and mozart validate work without conductor.
  Alternatives: (1) Keep dual-path — rejected because it doubled the test surface
  and caused subtle bugs. (2) Auto-start conductor on mozart run — rejected because
  daemon lifecycle should be explicit.
